Tests of different cluster methods

BSCdata <- subset(BSCdata,select = 
                    c("rich_moss","rich_lichen","rich_cyal",
                      "RMo","RLi","RCA",
                      "BM","TSW","cvPP",
                      "SOM","TN","TP","TK",
                      "silt","clay","pH","Ca","SS"))
fc <- subset(BSCdata, select = c("TSW","BM","cvPP",
                                "pH","SS","Ca","silt","clay",
                                "SOM","TN","TP","TK"))
sp <- subset(BSCdata, select =
               c("RCA","RLi","RMo"))
data_heat <- cor(sp$RCA, fc) %>% 
  rbind(cor(sp$RLi, fc)) %>% 
  rbind(cor(sp$RMo, fc))
row.names(data_heat) <- c("RCA","RLi","RMo")
colnames(data_heat) <- c("TSW","BM","cvPP","pH","SS","Ca","Silt",
                         "Clay","SOM","TN" ,"TP" ,"TK")

Plotting cluster results with different methods.

pheatmap(data_heat, cluster_row = FALSE,
         cutree_col = 4,treeheight_col=150,
         clustering_method= "centroid",main="centroid")

Clustering results are basically the same, except for the “single”, “median” and “centroid” method. But the “median” and “centroid” methods show reversed tree.

Tentative test of piecewiseSEM

As shown in cluster plot, many variables are clustered together. So, the ecological inference based on bi-variate correlations is unreliable. For example, the strong correlation between TP and RLi are highly likely from correlation between fine particle and RLi, or in opposite way. Therefor, factor analysis is key to find the latent or low-level cause behind the correlated variables. There is no latent variable in piecewise SEM, so we conduct the factor analysis separately.

BSCdata$fa1 <- fa(subset(BSCdata, select = c("TSW","BM","cvPP","SOM"),nfactors = 1,score=T))$scores
BSCdata$fa2 <- fa(subset(BSCdata, select = c("clay","silt","TP"),nfactors = 1,score=T))$scores
BSCdata$fa3 <- fa(subset(BSCdata, select = c("pH","Ca","SS"),nfactors = 1,score=T))$scores
pwm <- psem(
  lm(RMo ~ fa1 + fa2 + fa3 ,data=BSCdata),
  lm(RLi ~ fa1 + fa2 + fa3 ,data=BSCdata),
  lm(RCA ~ fa1 + fa2 + fa3 ,data=BSCdata)
)
summary(pwm)

The overall estimation fails with “Fisher’s C = 107.031 with P-value = 0 and on 6 degrees of freedom”, because indirect path is lacking. Apparently, a nested model with from continentality or longitude or region to clustered environmental factors to diversity pattern is promising for piecewiseSEM. However, the ecological topic in new model is beyond the scope of this article. limited by time, we plan to study the piecewiseSEM in the future.

Stepwise model adjustment

subdata <- subset(BSCdata,select = 
                    c("RMo","RLi","RCA",
                      "BM","TSW","cvPP",
                      "SOM","TN","TP","TK",
                      "silt","clay","pH","Ca","SS")) %>% 
  scale()%>% as.data.frame()
model0 <- '
group1 =~  TSW  + cvPP  + SOM  + BM
group2 =~  clay + silt  + TP
group3 =~  pH   + Ca    + SS  
RMo ~ group1 + group2 + group3 
RLi ~ group1 + group2 + group3 
RCA ~ group1 + group2 + group3 
'
fit0  <- sem(model0,data=subdata)
fitmeasures(fit0,fit.measures = c("chisq","df","pvalue","rmsea","tli","cfi"))

Path group3 =~ SS is not the weakest path, but the deletion of SS have the better fitting promotion. So we deleted the weakest manifested variables: BM TP SS.

model3 <- '
group1 =~  TSW  + cvPP
group2 =~  clay + silt
group3 =~  pH   + Ca  
RMo ~ group1 + group2 + group3 
RLi ~ group2
RCA ~ group1
'
